 must work against a real schema to catch syntax errors, column mismatches, and permission issues. Integration testing with a real PostgreSQL database verifies the runner can query _migrations correctly and skip already-applied migrations.","test_description":"Verify that after applying migration 001_initial.sql (which records an entry in the _migrations table), a subsequent run of the migration suite queries the _migrations table and skips 001_initial.sql without re-executing it, using a real PostgreSQL database instance to ensure the query syntax and table access work correctly.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.85,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"When a migration statement fails, its changes are rolled back automatically and no further migrations in the same run are attempted.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Transaction rollback is database-specific behavior that cannot be reliably mocked. A Unit test that mocks the database and mocks transaction.rollback() would pass even if the code never opens a transaction, never sets an error handler, or never calls rollback(). Only a real PostgreSQL database under Integration testing can verify: (a) a transaction is started, (b) a statement fails (e.g., CREATE INDEX on non-existent column), (c) the rollback is actually executed, (d) the prior state is restored (tables created by earlier statements are undone), and (e) subsequent migrations are not attempted. Mocking hides the real failure mode.","test_description":"Verify that when migration 002_bad.sql contains a failing statement (e.g., CREATE INDEX idx ON nonexistent_table), the runner catches the error, rolls back all changes from that migration file (any CREATE TABLE statements issued earlier in that migration are undone), does not record it in _migrations, and does not attempt to run migration 003_followup.sql, using a real PostgreSQL database to observe the actual transaction and rollback behavior.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.92,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.01}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"When two instances of the runner start at the same time against the same database, each migration is applied exactly once across both instances.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Race conditions and database locking behavior are invisible to Unit and single-process Integration tests. A Unit test can't simulate two processes starting simultaneously. An Integration test with a real database but a single process also can't expose the race: both instances reading _migrations before either records, both seeing migration 001 is missing, both attempting to apply it, and filesystem or database locks determining who succeeds. Only a System-level test with multiple real Node.js processes launching concurrently against a real PostgreSQL database exposes lock contention, serialization failures, and the actual outcome of concurrent writes to _migrations. This is the true failure boundary.","test_description":"Verify that when two separate Node.js processes launch concurrently and both attempt to run the migration suite against the same PostgreSQL database, migration 001_initial.sql is applied exactly once (not twice), the _migrations table has exactly one entry for 001_initial, and both processes complete without errors or duplicate-key violations, using a real PostgreSQL database and real OS process-level concurrency (e.g., spawning child processes with spawn() and letting them start simultaneously).","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.88,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"On the very first run against a fresh database, the _migrations table is created before any migration file is applied.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Creating the _migrations table via CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS is 